GB 18030-2022
Information Expansion Technology Chinese Coded Character Set
1 This document specifies the hexadecimal representation of Chinese graphic characters and even binary codes for use in information technology.
This document applies to the processing, exchange, storage, transmission, display, input and output of Chinese and other text graphic character information.
This document applies to technical products that have the function of information processing and exchange of Chinese and other text and graphic characters, including but not limited to software products represented by input methods, optical character recognition (OCR), editing and proofreading, machine translation, speech synthesis, text transcription, and smart writing, as well as software products represented by computers, communication terminal equipment, e-book readers, and learning machines.
2 Regulatory References
The contents of the following documents constitute the essential terms of this document through normative references in the text.
For referenced documents with dates, only the version corresponding to that date is applicable to this document; for referenced documents without dates, the latest version (including all amendments) is applicable to this document.
GB/T 2312-1980 &quot;Chinese Character Coded Character Set for Information Interchange&quot; Basic Set
GB/I 11383-1989 Information Processing - Eight-bit code structure and encoding rules for information exchange
GB/Gong13000 Information Technology Universal Multi-Octet Coded Character Set (UCS)
3 Terms and definitions
For the purposes of this document, the following terms and definitions apply.
3.1 character
An element in a collection of elements used to organize, control, or present data.
3.2 coded character
Characters (3.1) and their encodings are shown.
3.3 Private use area
The area where the user of the product conforming to this document may define himself.
3.4 Vocabulary repertoire
A specified set of characters (3.1) represented by a coded character set (3.2).
3.5 Reserved Zone
Area reserved for future regulation by this document.
GB 18030-2022
4 Vocabulary
4.1 Overview
The characters included in this document are encoded in single-byte, double-byte or four-byte encodings.
The single-byte part includes all 128 characters from 0x00 to 0x7F of GB/T 11383-1989.
4.3 Double-byte part
The double-byte part includes all graphic characters in GB/T 2312-1980, CJK unified Chinese characters in GB/T 13000, and some graphic characters.
The characters in the double-byte part are in accordance with the provisions in Appendix A.
The graphics, code positions and functions of ideographic descriptors shall comply with the provisions of Appendix B.
Note: GB/T 13000 is a unified code for Chinese characters used in China, Japan, Indonesia, Vietnam and other countries and regions.
Chinese characters with unique abstract glyphs are assigned separate code positions; Chinese characters with different sources but the same abstract glyphs are assigned shared code positions.
The encoded Chinese characters are called CJK Unified Ideographs, where CJK stands for China, Japan, and Korea.
4.4 Four-byte part
The four-byte part includes the 66 CJK unified Chinese characters in GB/T 13000 (9FA6-9FEF, excluding the 8 characters 9FB4~9FBB) in addition to the above-mentioned double-byte characters, CJK unified Chinese character extension A, CJK unified Chinese character extension BC, CJK unified Chinese character extension C, CJK unified Chinese character extension DC, CJK unified Chinese character extension D, CJK unified Chinese character extension F and the characters of minority languages that have been encoded in GB/T 13000.
The characters in the four-byte part are as specified in Appendix C.
5 Overall structure
In the text, numbers preceded by 0x are in hexadecimal, and numbers not preceded by 0x are in decimal.
All codes in the appendix are expressed in hexadecimal, and other numbers are expressed in decimal.
The single-byte part adopts the encoding structure of GB/T 11383-1989, using code points 0x00~0x7F.
The double-word part uses two 8-bit binary bit strings to represent a character, with the first byte code position from 0x81 to 0xFE, and the last byte code positions are 0x40 to 0x7E and 0x80 to 0xFE respectively.
The four-byte part uses 0x30-0x39 which is not used in GB/T 11383-1989 as the suffix to expand the double-byte encoding. The encoding range is 0x81308130-0xFE39FE39.
The encoding range of the first byte of a four-byte character is 0x81 to 0xFE; the encoding range of the second byte is 0x30 to 0x39; the encoding range of the third byte is 0x81 to 0xFE; the encoding range of the fourth byte is 0x30 to 0x39. That is: 0x81308130 to 0x81308139; 0x81308230 to 0x81308239 0x8130FEFE30 to 0x8130FE39; 0x81318130 to 0x81318139; Oo2douolag0c “0URo23061393 0xFE39FE30 to 0xFE39FE39.
