DESCRIPTION The C and C++ compilers are integrated. They both process input files in one or more of four steps: preprocessing, Hii (compilation), (assembly) MERE (linking).
The source file suffix identifies the language of the source file, but for the compiler, the suffix controls the default settings:
gcc considers the preprocessed file (.i) to be a c file, and sets the c-style link.
g++ considers the preprocessed file (.i) to be a C++ file and sets the linker to C++.
The source file&#39;s suffix indicates the language and subsequent operations:
.c C source program; preprocessing, compilation, assembly
