Executive Summary
The impact of COVID-19 on the drug market
The impact could be similar to the 2008 economic crisis
The global COVID-19 pandemic has plunged the world into an unprecedented crisis.
The disease has overwhelmed health services in many countries, and restrictions imposed by governments have caused severe disruptions in the global economy.
The impact of the epidemic on drug markets is unclear and difficult to predict, but it is likely to be far-reaching.
Some producers may be forced to find new ways to make drugs as restrictions on movement also limit access to precursors and basic chemicals.
Traffickers, unable to cross borders due to travel restrictions, may have to find new routes and methods.
Patterns of drug use and supply may change and the ability of governments to respond may be hampered.
The changes brought about by COVID-19 are unprecedented, but there are still some lessons to be learned from previous crises.
After the 2008 economic crisis, some drug users began looking for cheaper synthetic substances and usage patterns shifted to injecting drugs.
At the same time, governments cut drug-related budgets.
If governments respond to the current recession in the same way, interventions to prevent drug use and related risk behaviours, and drug treatment services, are likely to be hit hard.
Furthermore, interdiction operations and international cooperation may be given lower priority, making it easier for traffickers to operate.
The direct impact on drug trafficking in countries where large quantities of drugs are smuggled on commercial flights is expected to be greatest.
Couriers carry synthetic drugs such as methamphetamine in carry-on backpacks or concealed in personal luggage, sometimes in large quantities. With restrictions on air passenger transport imposed almost everywhere, the use of commercial air travel to supply drugs could be completely disrupted.
While international postal supply chains have also been disrupted, trafficking using the dark web and cargo mailings is likely to increase.
In the long term, economic recession and related lockdown measures could disrupt drug markets.
Due to rising unemployment and lack of opportunity, poor and vulnerable populations will be more likely to use drugs in harmful ways, develop drug use disorders and turn to illegal drug-related activities - whether production or transportation.
Drug trafficking organizations may take advantage of this situation, offering their services to vulnerable populations and recruiting new members to expand their ranks.
As governments’ capacity to respond decreases, these shifts are likely to take root quickly and become the new reality for many communities.
Expansion and complexity
Market growth
Population growth patterns partially explain market expansion
Drug abuse has been increasing around the world, both in terms of overall figures and as a percentage of the world&#39;s population.
In 2009, there were an estimated 210 million drug users, accounting for 4.8% of the global population aged 15-64, while in 2018, there were an estimated 269 million drug users, accounting for 5.3% of this population.
Over the past two decades, drug abuse has increased much faster in developing countries than in developed countries.
This partly reflects differences in overall population growth over the period, 7% in developed countries and 28% in developing countries, but also reflects faster growth in the younger population in developing countries.
Teenagers and young adults make up the largest proportion of drug users.
Between 2000 and 2018, the population in this age group grew by 16% in developing countries, while it fell by 10% in developed countries.
1 Urbanization is a driver of current and future drug markets
In both developed and developing countries, drug abuse is more common in urban areas than in rural areas.
The overall increase in drug abuse is partly due to the massive migration of people from rural to urban areas - more than half of the world&#39;s population now lives in urban areas, compared with 34 per cent in 1960.
Urbanization is likely to be a key factor in the future dynamics of drug markets, particularly in developing countries where urbanization trends are more pronounced.
Increased wealth is associated with increased drug use, but it is the poorest people who bear the greatest burden of disease. Worldwide, drug use is more common in developed countries than in developing countries.
Drugs such as cocaine are particularly strongly associated with wealthier parts of the world.
Likewise, within countries, the prevalence of drug abuse is higher among wealthier segments of society.
But the rate of transition to drug use disorders is higher among people of lower socioeconomic status.
Data from a few countries suggest a link between harmful drug use patterns and health conditions and low income.
These patterns appear to be less common in wealthier social classes.
Economic constraints caused by the global COVID-19 crisis are likely to exacerbate risks for the most vulnerable groups, including people who use drugs.
For example, changes in labor markets, such as rising unemployment, have been associated with increases in drug use in the past, and the pandemic has forced tens of millions of people out of work worldwide.
COVID-19 may lead to further expansion of the drug market The COVID-19 pandemic may cause more farmers to increase or engage in illegal crop cultivation, either because the control capacity of national authorities is reduced or because more people may be forced to take risks and engage in illegal activities due to the economic crisis.
Trafficking at sea may have increased as a result of reduced air and land traffic as a result of COVID-19-related restrictions, as the risk of interception at sea is low and there are more smuggled people than by air or land.
There have been recent reports of cocaine shipments being shipped directly from South America to Europe by sea.
Increased complexity
The emergence of substances not under international control is stable, but new and potentially harmful opioids are increasing and drug markets are becoming increasingly complex.
In addition to plant-based substances such as cannabis, cocaine and heroin, hundreds of synthetic drugs have been added, many of which are not under international control. The non-medical use of drugs has also increased rapidly.
Around 500 new active substances enter the domestic markets of the Member States every year.
Currently, most of these are stimulants, followed by synthetic cannabinoid receptor agonists and a small amount of opioids.
While the overall number of new psychoactive substances has stabilized, the proportions have changed.
In 2014, opioid-type new psychoactive substances accounted for only 2% of the total number of new psychoactive substances identified, but by 2018, this figure had risen to 9%.
Many of the opioid new psychoactive substances are analogs of fentanyl, which have demonstrated efficacy and harm and have caused overdose deaths in North America and, to a lesser extent, in other regions.
In North America, fentanyl is used as an adulterator in heroin and other drugs, including cocaine and methamphetamine, and in the manufacture of counterfeit pharmaceutical opioids.
There is some evidence that NPS doping is also taking place in Europe: a study of discarded syringe residues in six European cities found that many syringes were contaminated with NPS that produce stimulant effects.
2. Use of new psychoactive substances may become entrenched among vulnerable groups
There has almost never been a large market for a single type of NPS.
But evidence from Europe suggests synthetic cannabinoids are a serious problem among marginalized groups such as the homeless and prison inmates.
Twenty-two countries reported on the use of new psychoactive substances in prisons, with the majority identifying synthetic cannabinoids as a major challenge.
Control of precursor chemicals forces drug manufacturers to innovate Many of the chemicals most commonly used as precursors in the synthesis of drugs such as amphetamine, methamphetamine and &quot;ecstasy&quot; are already under international control.
Drug traffickers and manufacturers are constantly searching for substitutes—not only less-regulated substances but also chemicals designed specifically to circumvent regulations, so-called “designer precursors.”
Restrictive measures aimed at stopping the spread of COVID-19 are likely to further squeeze drug makers who rely on precursor chemicals.
Evidence from Mexico suggests that this is already happening: in March 2020, reported shortages of methamphetamine precursors imported from East Asia prompted an increase in methamphetamine prices in Mexico and the United States.
The market is changing rapidly
Synthetic drugs replace opiates in Central Asia and the Russian Federation
The opiate markets in Central Asia and the Russian Federation appear to have changed between 2008 and 2018.
The amount of opiates seized by Russian federal authorities fell by about 80 per cent, while the number of people receiving treatment for opioid use dropped significantly.
But the market for stimulants seems to be booming.
There is evidence that methamphetamine and various cathinones, including mephedrone and a-pyrrolidinophenvalerophenone, are now widely available on the Russian drug market.
Russian authorities have reported a recent sharp rise in the number of clandestine laboratories manufacturing a variety of illicit drugs, more than doubling in two years to 152 laboratories in 2018.
Methamphetamine markets grow in Afghanistan and Iraq
As early as 2012, surveys of personnel in hospitals, prisons and other institutions revealed the importance of methamphetamine in Iraq.
Crystalline methamphetamine has become another major drug of concern, alongside Captagon and Tramadol.
A 2015 study further confirmed these findings, with drug users stating that cannabis was more difficult to obtain than Captagon or methamphetamine.
Recently, the Iraqi authorities have uncovered several methamphetamine laboratories and the Board has expressed concern about the large importation of pseudoephedrine preparations, which are used as precursors in methamphetamine laboratories.
In Afghanistan, methamphetamine manufacture appears to have begun in 2014.
Since then, methamphetamine seizures have been rising steadily.
But seizures in the first half of 2019 totaled 1,657 kilograms - a sharp jump from the previous year.
Large seizures of methamphetamine believed to have originated in Afghanistan have been made in other countries, also suggesting that production in that country is rising rapidly.
Policy changes and changing trends
Most jurisdictions that have legalized non-medical cannabis use have seen an increase in cannabis use
Canada, Uruguay and 11 jurisdictions in the United States allow the manufacture of cannabis products for non-medical use.
In most of these jurisdictions, cannabis use has increased since legalization, although the same trend has been observed in other jurisdictions that have not legalized the non-medical use of cannabis.
In Colorado and Washington, two of the first states to pass legislation in the United States, non-medical marijuana use among adults has increased, particularly in the past month and daily or almost daily, and has exceeded the national average since 2012.
All indicators show that cannabis use has increased in Uruguay since 2011, with use almost doubling in the last month.
This suggests that the main reason for the increase is regular and frequent cannabis use.
Short-term data from Canada also suggest that use increased as the legal market expanded from 2018 to 2019.
However, 40% of cannabis users in 2019 still obtained some products from illegal sources.
Is legalization behind the plunge in global cannabis herb seizures?
Global cannabis herb seizures fell to their lowest level in 20 years in 2018, driven by a drop in seizures in North America, which have fallen 84 per cent over the past decade.
In contrast, seizures in the rest of the world almost doubled during the same period. The pattern of seizures suggests that policies aimed at liberalizing the cannabis market played a key role in the decline.
Regulation of new psychoactive substances appears to have a deterrent effect The effectiveness of regulation of new psychoactive substances in China remains difficult to assess.
Some countries with different regulatory regimes for NPS show different prevalence rates of NPS use.
In other countries, the use of new psychoactive substances has decreased following the adoption of domestic legislation.
Vulnerable groups face harms from legal and illegal drug markets Medicinal opioids for pain management and palliative care are available mainly in high-income countries Pain medications are unevenly distributed across regions.
In 2018, more than 90% of all pharmaceutical opioids available for medical consumption were in high-income countries.
About 50% are in North America, 40% in Europe, and 2% in Oceania.
These countries account for approximately 12% of the world&#39;s population.
Low- and middle-income countries are estimated to be home to 88% of the world’s population but consume less than 10% of pharmaceutical opioids.
Barriers to accessing pharmaceutical opioids are related to many factors, including legislation, culture, health systems, and prescribing practices.
Poorer people are at greater risk of developing a drug use disorder. In 2018, an estimated 35.6 million people had a drug use disorder.
Poverty, limited education, and social marginalization can increase the risk of substance use disorders and exacerbate their consequences. This is supported by studies in high-income countries, where an individual’s adverse socioeconomic trajectory—not just their situation at a single point in time—is associated with risk of substance use disorders.
Drug use disorders can also reinforce socioeconomic disadvantage, further increasing the risk of unemployment, poverty and homelessness, thus contributing to a vicious cycle of disadvantage. These outcomes can also be linked to stigmatizing attitudes and outcomes within the criminal justice system.
Women, ethnic minorities and migrants, sexually diverse groups, people displaced by armed conflict or disaster, and people in rural settings may also be disproportionately affected by drug use disorders or face problems accessing treatment services.
The broader societal impact of harmful drug use has increased over the past decade, as measured by the Disability Adjusted Life Year (DALY) metric, which estimates the number of years of healthy life lost due to disability and premature death.
Between 2007 and 2018, the number of global disability-adjusted life years attributable to drug use increased by 17%.
The increase in DALYs associated with liver cancer, caused by untreated hepatitis C, which is common among injecting drug users, was particularly high — 40 percent.
The relationship between drugs and violence is complex and it is difficult to identify all causal relationships between psychoactive substance use and violence.
Limited data from around the world suggest that intoxication may be a significant factor in homicides.
But alcohol appears to play a bigger role than drugs in violent incidents.
While drug use may lead to crime, in some cases this association can be partially attributed to a variety of mediating factors, such as socioeconomic disadvantage and other types of adversity caused by personal risk, family environment, and peer influence.
The links between drug trafficking and violence are multifaceted.
Large-scale organized crime, including international drug trafficking, can be carried out without violence if stable criminal structures already exist.
In the short term, the presence and extent of violence depend less on the volume of trafficking than on certain changes that destabilize the balance of power among organized criminal groups, such as changes in the size of illegal markets, the death or imprisonment of high-profile criminals, and law enforcement measures that make one group weaker than another.
Latest Trends
Marijuana is the most commonly used substance, opioids are the most harmful
An estimated 192 million people used cannabis in 2018, making it the most used drug in the world.
By comparison, 58 million people used opioids in 2018.
However, the hazards associated with opioids have been overlooked due to the small number of users.
Such substances were responsible for 66 per cent of the estimated 167,000 deaths related to drug use disorders in 2017, and 50 per cent of the 21 million years of life lost due to disability or premature death believed to be attributable to drug use.
Non-medical use of synthetic opioids exacerbates public health crisis
In West, Central and North Africa, it’s tramadol that’s fueling the opioid crisis; in North America, it’s fentanyl. The two regions share little in common in terms of their economies, demographics or general patterns of drug use, but both are struggling to combat an opioid crisis fueled by substances that are easily available and cheap to produce.
In North America, the use of synthetic opioids such as fentanyl has led to a 20-year increase in opioid overdose deaths.
In 2018, two-thirds of the 67,367 overdose deaths registered in the United States involved fentanyl.
Canada reported similar results, albeit at a lower level.
Fentanyl overdose deaths are partly due to the unpredictable effects of fentanyl on the illicit drug market.
The market for non-medical tramadol has grown significantly in West Africa, Central Africa and North Africa.
In the region, an increasing number of patients with tramadol use disorders are receiving treatment.
In 2017, the amount of tramadol seized globally increased significantly, reaching a peak of more than 125 tons.
But in 2018, after India passed a new law regulating tramadol, global seizures fell to 32 tons.
Contributing to the crises in both places is the simplicity of manufacturing and low production costs, as well as the lack of international regulation of tramadol and many fentanyl analogs or their precursors.
Exacerbating the crises in both places is the availability of these substances on both the pharmaceutical and illicit markets, making their detection and prevention more difficult.
Stimulant use is increasing
The stimulant sector is dominated by cocaine and methamphetamine, both of which are seeing increasing use in their major markets.
An estimated 19 million people used cocaine in 2018, as the drug is popular in North America and Western Europe.
In the same year, approximately 27 million people used amphetamines, with methamphetamine being the most commonly used amphetamine-type stimulant in Southeast Asia and North America.
According to most available indicators, methamphetamine use has been increasing in both regions over the past 20 years.
In some markets, cocaine and methamphetamine can coexist, sometimes as substitutes for each other so that use of one drug increases while use of the other decreases, and sometimes both increasing and decreasing simultaneously to meet demand in the same market.
COVID-19 puts injecting drug users at increased risk
It is estimated that in 2018, there were approximately 11.3 million people who injected drugs, and approximately 10% of global HIV infections were caused by injecting drug use.
More than 1 million people who inject drugs are infected with HIV and 5.5 million are infected with hepatitis C.
In 2017, approximately 585,000 people died from drug abuse, half of whom died from liver disease caused by hepatitis C, while hepatitis C among injecting drug users remains mostly untreated.
5 Opioid shortages caused by COVID-19 restrictions may lead users to substitute more readily available substances such as alcohol or benzodiazepines, or to mix opioids with synthetic drugs.
As some users switch to injecting or inject more frequently, more harmful patterns of use may emerge.
