EU summit debates refugee policy, EU officials: reception process full of bottlenecks - China News Service
EU summit argues over refugee policy, EU officials: bottlenecks exist at every step of the reception process
[Global Times special correspondent in Belgium Niu Ruifei] According to a report by AFP on February 10, at the latest EU summit that day, European Commission President von der Leyen said that EU leaders agreed to introduce stricter policies on illegal immigration to make it easier to expel illegal immigrants.
The EU&#39;s move is reportedly a response to Europe&#39;s growing concern about illegal immigration, with the core problem for the EU today being that very few illegal immigrants are ultimately deported.
According to the summit document, EU leaders called on the Commission to &quot;immediately mobilise substantial EU funds&quot; to strengthen external borders, including with infrastructure and surveillance.
However, the EU and member states are arguing over issues such as payment for the fence.
Von der Leyen has repeatedly said that EU funds will not cover the costs.
But diplomats from some member states say that if the EU could share the cost of installing cameras, watchtowers and other infrastructure along its external borders, it would free up national budgets and speed up construction.
According to the European Euractiv website, EU officials admitted that there are bottlenecks at every step of the refugee reception process. Limited reception capacity and overwhelmed immigration authorities in member states cannot prevent refugees from submitting &quot;countless&quot; asylum applications in EU countries. The EU&#39;s refugee reception system is in a near &quot;permanent crisis.&quot;
According to the European Commission, the EU&#39;s Schengen countries received more than 920,000 asylum applications last year, an increase of nearly half from the previous year.
Meanwhile, the European Union recorded more than 330,000 illegal entries last year.
Against this backdrop, the summit also reached an agreement on a “principle” that EU countries can deport illegal immigrants based on a court ruling in another member state.
In addition, the report said that EU leaders also agreed to &quot;increase the use of the concept of safe countries&quot;, which will pave the way for the EU to develop a common list.
