The United States escalates the &quot;chip war&quot; and hits the global semiconductor industry hard - China News Network
Recently, the U.S. &quot;chip war&quot; against China has shown signs of escalating - first, under pressure from the United States, the Netherlands and Japan agreed to initiate export controls on semiconductor manufacturing equipment to China; later, foreign media reported that the U.S. government was considering cutting off all ties between U.S. suppliers and Huawei and prohibiting U.S. suppliers from providing any products to Huawei; the Biden administration is also preparing to issue an executive order to restrict U.S. investment in sensitive Chinese technology industries... Shortly after the beginning of 2023, the United States has been using vicious tricks to curb the development of China&#39;s semiconductor-related industries.
In recent years, the United States has never stopped its efforts to crack down on China&#39;s &quot;chip&quot; development. On the one hand, it has precisely suppressed China&#39;s semiconductor production and supply chain, while on the other hand, it has built a &quot;de-Sinicized&quot; semiconductor industry chain alliance, attempting to completely &quot;leave&quot; China behind in the advanced semiconductor industry.
Whether it is wooing South Korea to establish a &quot;technological alliance&quot;, or establishing a chip &quot;Quad&quot; with South Korea, Japan and Taiwan, China, or using the &quot;Quadrilateral Security Dialogue&quot; and &quot;Indo-Pacific Economic Framework&quot; mechanisms to establish a &quot;small circle&quot; of the semiconductor industry chain, the United States is introducing politicized, factionalized and weaponized means into the semiconductor industry, attempting to build a closed production and supply chain cycle dominated by the United States, thereby making up for its shortcomings in the chip manufacturing field and maintaining its dominant position in the global chip industry.
