According to professional estimates, based on specialized division of labor, the entire production process of semiconductor products needs to cross borders of various countries more than 70 times and the entire process takes up to 100 days.
Although the U.S. semiconductor industry has a strong foundation, it is relatively weak in manufacturing capabilities, especially advanced process technology, and is heavily dependent on East Asia.
Even if the United States tries its best to guide the production and supply chain of advanced chips to shift to a &quot;small circle&quot; regional development dominated by the United States, the regional distribution and interdependence of global semiconductor-related industries will be difficult to change.
