The fitness industry should get rid of the crisis of trust - China News Network
Another large gym goes bankrupt?
Recently, the issue of rights protection of members of Zhongjian Fitness, a well-known fitness institution, has attracted social attention.
After the Spring Festival, many members found that the store they were in was not operating normally. Subsequently, rumors about the institution’s bankruptcy caused panic among members, leading to the intervention of the public security and human resources departments.
Finally, the relevant person in charge of the organization came forward to respond and promised to work hard to protect the legal rights and interests of employees and members, and the storm was calmed down.
Some stores of some fitness institutions have encountered operational problems and have been temporarily closed. Consumers could have remained calm and waited for the problems to be resolved. Why are many members&#39; first reaction &quot;something bad is happening&quot;?
Behind the fitness club members’ rights protection storm is the deep-seated problem of the industry’s trust crisis.
Traditional gyms in China generally adopt a prepaid payment model, and “making money without users coming” is the underlying logic of their development.
Obtaining cash flow through pre-selling membership cards and continuously opening new stores seems to be a repeatable cycle, but in reality it is living beyond one&#39;s means and cannot form a stable profit model.
Negative information in the industry, such as gyms running away, has frequently been reported, causing a strong impact on consumer confidence.
From the perspective of market prospects, gyms are certainly a good business with &quot;money prospects&quot;.
Although the fitness industry has experienced ups and downs, it has always attracted attention from capital.
Multiple data show that the popularity of cultural and sports consumption and other fields is constantly rising, and the market continues to recover.
Specifically in the fitness market, as residents&#39; living standards steadily improve and the concept of healthy living becomes deeply rooted in people&#39;s hearts, the fitness industry has great potential for development.
The better the situation becomes, the more the industry needs to pay attention to development quality.
However, some institutions are blindly optimistic about the fitness market after the consumption recovery. Just after emerging from the crisis, they sound the clarion call for expansion and invest all the financing funds into building new stores.
It is undeniable that due to the impact of the epidemic in recent years, many institutions have withdrawn and the industry has been reshuffled. It may be a new opportunity for capable companies to selectively increase their acquisition efforts and re-position their positions at this time.
However, if the fitness market wants to enter a virtuous cycle and embark on a long-term and steady path, the industry must change its traditional model and business strategy.
Only by taking steady steps and rebuilding consumers&#39; trust and sense of security can we truly win the market and the future.
Compared with building new stores to seize market share, what the fitness industry needs now is to calm down and optimize services and use high-quality development to retain users.
First of all, we need to retain users through service.
Gyms belong to the service industry, and their essence is to adhere to the &quot;user orientation&quot;, focus closely on user needs, and focus their operations on improving service quality.
Secondly, we must rely on digital transformation to improve user experience.
For example, the currently popular Internet gym model allows users to pay per visit and choose the venue themselves.
At the same time, physical data and sports data can be effectively utilized to meet social needs and achieve a complete service closed loop from online to offline.
Without personal training sales pitches and huge annual membership fees, users’ concerns about fitness organizations “running away” are reduced, and their sense of trust is enhanced.
In addition, we must actively explore diversified business formats.
Nowadays, sports consumption has shifted from single services to scenario consumption. Fitness clubs are expected to become a new entry point for consumption. Peripheral products such as sports supplies and fitness equipment required for fitness may become new profit points, providing consumers with more choices.
Jiang Tianjiao
