Taiwan&#39;s economy starts the year poorly as multiple data show decline - Chinanews.com
Xinhua News Agency, Taipei, February 11 (Reporters Zhao Bo and Huang Yang) The export trade volume has been &quot;black for five consecutive months&quot;, the manufacturing purchasing managers&#39; index (PMI) has tightened for seven consecutive months, and the consumer price index (CPI) has returned to the &quot;3-digit&quot; level... Recently, the Taiwan authorities have successively released economic data for January 2023.
Experts believe that Taiwan&#39;s economic performance at the beginning of the year was poor and the pressure on growth was considerable.
According to the Taiwan authorities&#39; financial affairs department, Taiwan&#39;s exports in January this year were US$31.51 billion, a year-on-year decrease of 21.2%, marking the fifth consecutive month of negative growth.
The export value of 11 major export categories all declined compared with the same period last year.
Plastics, rubber and their products, and optical equipment experienced the largest declines, down 37.6% and 35.7% year-on-year respectively.
Exports of electronic components fell 20.1% year-on-year, the biggest drop in 11 years.
Among them, integrated circuits fell 18.3% year-on-year, the biggest drop in 14 years.
Cai Meina, director of the department&#39;s statistics department, said this shows that the effect of weak demand in the consumer electronics industry has spread and the electronics industry has entered a correction period.
Statistics show that Taiwan&#39;s imports and exports both fell in January, with the trade surplus amounting to only US$2.34 billion, the lowest level in the past three years.
The Taiwan authorities&#39; financial affairs department believes that the global terminal demand has decreased, and the industry&#39;s inventory adjustment has suppressed manufacturers&#39; willingness to purchase materials. The export slump is unlikely to improve in the short term, and Taiwan&#39;s export decline in the first quarter of this year may be higher than expected.
According to the Taiwan Institute for Economic Research, Taiwan&#39;s manufacturing purchasing managers&#39; index (PMI) was 40.4% in January this year after seasonal adjustment, a further drop of 3.3 percentage points from December last year, and has been tightening for seven consecutive months.
In the economic monitoring indicator system, PMI uses 50% as the boom-bust line. An index greater than 50% represents economic expansion, and vice versa.
Among the five components of Taiwan&#39;s PMI in January, new orders, production and labor employment tightened, supplier delivery time decreased, and inventory tightened.
All six major industries reported a contraction in the PMI, and the industries were ranked in order of contraction speed as follows: power and machinery equipment industry (35.1%), electronics and optics industry (35.2%), chemicals and biotechnology and medical industry (39.2%), basic raw materials industry (42.4%), transportation industry (42.6%) and food and textile industry (45.7%).
In terms of prices, the Taiwan authorities&#39; Directorate-General of Budget, Accounting and Statistics announced that Taiwan&#39;s CPI year-on-year growth rate was 3.04% in January this year, breaking through 3% again since July last year.
Among them, vegetable prices soared 28.25%, hitting a 17-month high.
Cao Zhihong, a special commissioner of Taiwan&#39;s Directorate-General of Budget, Accounting and Statistics, admitted that the increase in vegetable prices was indeed beyond expectations. Excluding the Spring Festival factor, the average CPI in January and February this year should be close to 2.71% in December last year. Inflationary pressure still exists and is still at a high point.
Looking ahead to Taiwan&#39;s economy this year, experts are pessimistic based on reports from local media including the United Daily News and Yahoo Finance.
Wu Daren, professor of economics at Taiwan&#39;s National Central University, analyzed that the decline in exports may cause cash flow problems for export manufacturing companies and increase the risk of debt default.
At the same time, the reduction in orders has led manufacturers to cut labor costs, affecting the labor market and family economy, which in turn has impacted consumer spending power.
Chiu Ta-sheng, a researcher at the Taiwan Institute of Economics, believes that the inflation situation in Europe and the United States has not been resolved this year and demand continues to shrink. He estimates that Taiwan&#39;s export recession will continue into the first half of the year.
Since Taiwan&#39;s economy is supported by exports, the full-year economic growth performance will be worse than last year due to the sluggish exports.
