(Deutsche Welle Chinese website) Several days have passed since the earthquake struck parts of Turkey and Syria, and the hope of finding survivors is becoming increasingly slim. However, the family of five rescued on Saturday made the search and rescue workers feel extremely relieved.
According to the Associated Press, the family of five was successfully rescued after being trapped under the rubble for more than five days in the hard-hit town of Noorday in Gaziantep province.
Rescuers first pulled the mother and daughter out of the rubble, and then found the father, but he insisted on saving his son and another daughter first.
When they were all rescued, cheers broke out among the crowd.
In the southern Turkish city of Kahramanmaraş, a 16-year-old boy and a 70-year-old woman were also successfully rescued in severe cold weather conditions.
&quot;What day is today?
&quot;- The teenager who was trapped under the rubble for 129 hours asked the rescuers who rescued him after being brought back to the ground.
A man in Kahramanmaraş holds his rescued cat
The miraculous successful rescue case brought a ray of hope to the search and rescue work, which had already been hopeless. However, at the same time, the death toll continued to rise.
According to official statistics, Monday&#39;s earthquake has killed more than 20,000 people in Türkiye, and the death toll in neighboring Syria is estimated to be more than 3,500.
Although experts say people trapped in the rubble can survive for more than a week, the hope of finding more survivors has become increasingly slim.
Rescuers are still using thermal imaging cameras to search for signs of life beneath the rubble.
At the same time, the focus of rescue efforts began to shift to helping survivors in urgent need of help.
UN official: The region&#39;s disaster is &#39;unprecedented in a century&#39;
Martin Griffiths, the UN Under-Secretary-General for Humanitarian Affairs and Emergency Relief Coordinator, said at a press conference in Turkey that the earthquake was &quot;the worst disaster in a century&quot; to hit the region.
He also praised Türkiye&#39;s post-disaster response as &quot;extraordinary.&quot;
He also told Reuters he hoped to deliver aid to areas controlled by both the Syrian government and opposition, but said that was &quot;still unclear&quot;.
The United Nations has pledged an additional $25 million in relief aid to earthquake-stricken people in Syria.
Earlier this week, the United Nations announced $25 million in disaster relief for Türkiye and Syria.
The most destructive earthquake in the world in 60 years
Chile earthquake (1960)
At 3:11 p.m. local time on May 22, 1960, the largest earthquake ever recorded in human history occurred in Valdivia, Chile, with a moment magnitude of 9.5.
In just ten minutes, the entire city of Valdivia was reduced to ruins.
The huge tsunami caused by the earthquake hit the Chilean coastline, creating a huge tsunami with a wave height of 25 meters.
The tsunami affected countries as far away as Japan and the Philippines.
The exact number of casualties and economic losses caused by a disaster of this scale cannot be known.
The most destructive earthquake in the world in 60 years
Great Alaska Earthquake (1964)
March 27, 1964 was a Friday, also Good Friday.
On this day, the largest earthquake in North American history occurred in Alaska, USA, with a moment magnitude of 9.2.
As of 2006, the Alaska earthquake was still the third largest earthquake ever recorded in the world.
The earthquake occurred when a fault between the Pacific and North American plates ruptured in Prince William Sound near College Sound.
The earthquake lasted between three and five minutes in most areas.
The displacement of the seabed triggered a massive tsunami with a height of 67 meters.
Because it was a holiday, schools and many businesses were closed.
The earthquake ultimately killed 139 people.
Nine people died directly from the earthquake, and the other 130 died from the tsunami caused by the earthquake.
The most destructive earthquake in the world in 60 years
Tangshan Earthquake (1976)
On July 28, 1976, two strong earthquakes of magnitude 7 or above occurred in Tangshan City and Fengnan County, Hebei Province, China within 16 hours.
The epicenter was 23 kilometers above the ground.
The entire city of Tangshan was razed to the ground in an instant as transportation, communications, water supply and electricity were cut off.
The capital Beijing, 140 kilometers away, also felt strong tremors.
According to official statistics, the earthquake caused 242,769 deaths and 164,851 serious injuries in all affected areas, including Beijing and Tianjin.
The Tangshan earthquake became the second deadliest earthquake in China&#39;s recorded history, second only to the Jiajing earthquake in 1556.
But some overseas scientists estimate that the earthquake may have killed at least 650,000 people.
The most destructive earthquake in the world in 60 years
Indian Ocean earthquake (2004)
On December 26, 2004, an earthquake occurred 160 kilometers west of the Aceh Province on the island of Sumatra, Indonesia, with a focal depth of 30 kilometers and a moment magnitude of 9.1 to 9.3.
The earthquake triggered a huge tsunami with waves 15 to 30 meters high.
A total of 14 countries along the Pacific coast were affected, with the worst-hit areas including Indonesia&#39;s Aceh province, Thailand&#39;s Khao Lak and Phuket resort areas, Sri Lanka, and India&#39;s Tamil Nadu state.
It was the peak tourist season at Christmas, and a large number of tourists and local residents gathered in the disaster-stricken areas, causing many tourists enjoying their holidays on the beach and local people working on the seaside to be swept to the bottom of the sea by the tsunami, resulting in many people becoming missing in this earthquake.
It is estimated that the death toll and missing persons is at least 300,000.
The most destructive earthquake in the world in 60 years
Wenchuan Earthquake (2008)
On May 12, 2008, a major earthquake struck Wenchuan, Sichuan Province, China.
According to data from the China Earthquake Administration, the surface wave magnitude of the earthquake reached 8.2 and the moment magnitude reached 8.3, and the damaged area exceeded 100,000 square kilometers.
As of September 25, 2008, the earthquake caused 69,227 deaths, 17,923 missing persons, 374,643 injuries of varying degrees, 19.9303 million people lost their homes, and the total population affected reached 46.256 million.
It was the most destructive earthquake since the founding of the People&#39;s Republic of China and also the one with the heaviest casualties since the Tangshan earthquake.
In March 2009, China&#39;s State Council announced that May 12 of each year would be designated as Disaster Prevention and Reduction Day to strengthen public education and attention to disaster prevention and reduction work.
Since then, governments and primary and secondary schools in many parts of China have held earthquake drills on this day every year.
Primary and secondary schools have also begun to attach importance to popularizing &quot;earthquake prevention and disaster reduction&quot; education.
The most destructive earthquake in the world in 60 years
Haiti earthquake (2010)
On January 12, 2010, a magnitude 7.0 earthquake struck the Caribbean island nation of Haiti.
The epicenter was located 25 kilometers southwest of Port-au-Prince, the capital of Haiti, and the source was about 13 kilometers from the surface.
The International Red Cross estimates that the earthquake affected approximately 3 million people.
The Haitian government has announced that the confirmed death toll has exceeded 200,000.
In some parts of Haiti, up to 90% of the houses were destroyed in the earthquake.
Despite massive aid and support from the international community, the impoverished, overpopulated and corrupt country never recovered from the disaster.
The most destructive earthquake in the world in 60 years
Great Tohoku Earthquake (2011)
On March 11, 2011, a large thrust zone earthquake with a moment magnitude of 9.0 occurred off the coast of Tohoku, Japan.
The epicenter was located in the Pacific Ocean east of Sendai, the capital of Miyagi Prefecture. The depth of the epicenter was measured to be 24 kilometers, and it triggered a huge tsunami with a maximum height of 40.1 meters.
This earthquake is the first earthquake with a magnitude of more than 9 in Japan&#39;s history.
About 22,000 people were killed in the disaster and approximately 400,000 buildings were completely destroyed or collapsed.
The Fukushima Daiichi Nuclear Power Plant suffered a leak due to the earthquake and tsunami.
The accident was classified as Level 7, the most severe level, on the International Nuclear Event Scale (INES).
The Fukushima nuclear accident has resulted in trace amounts of radioactive substances being measured around the world, including iodine-131 and cesium-137 (with a half-life of 30 years).
A large amount of radioactive isotopes were released into the Pacific Ocean as a result of this nuclear accident.
According to UN statistics, at least 870,000 people are in urgent need of food in the disaster-stricken areas in Turkey and Syria.
In Syria alone, as many as 5.3 million people lost their homes due to the earthquake.
The World Food Programme (WFP) has appealed for $77 million to provide food to people displaced by the earthquakes in Türkiye and Syria.
Currently, the temperature in the disaster area is below zero and many victims have no shelter.
The Turkish government has distributed large quantities of hot meals, tents and blankets, but these supplies still have difficulty reaching many people in urgent need of help.
In Syria, which has been mired in civil war for 12 years, the earthquake has made the people&#39;s suffering even worse.
In the four days since the earthquake, the World Food Programme has provided food relief to 115,000 people in Türkiye and Syria.
The World Health Organization (WHO) sent 72 tons of medical supplies for trauma treatment and emergency surgery.
