Chongyang Q&amp;A | How to view the US January non-farm payrolls data that exceeded expectations and future trends - Economic Observer - Professional financial news website
Q: I would like to ask Zhongyang Investment, what do you think about the US January non-farm payroll data that exceeded expectations and future trends?
A: On February 3, the U.S. Department of Labor released non-farm employment data for January 2023, with 517,000 new non-farm jobs, significantly higher than the market expectation of 189,000; the unemployment rate dropped to 3.4%, the lowest level in nearly 50 years; the hourly wage growth rate was 4.4% year-on-year and 0.3% month-on-month, a slight slowdown.
From a total perspective, the data are disturbed by many one-off and technical factors, such as faculty and staff returning to work after a strike, revisions to the survey and statistical scope, and updates to seasonal adjustment factors. There may be subsequent revisions (refer to the January 2022 non-farm payrolls, which were revised down from 504,000 to 364,000), and non-farm employment may not be as strong as the data shows.
From a structural perspective, the impact of layoffs in high-tech companies is still there, but the proportion is relatively low; new employment in high-contact service industries such as leisure hotels, education and health care has rebounded significantly, and data shows that the labor gap in the service industry still exists.
Combined with the also-far-than-expected service industry PMI, the rebound in job vacancies and labor shortage data, and the strong consumer credit data, we judge that the U.S. service industry has experienced a rapid recovery after extreme weather and holidays.
We believe that the supply and demand tightness in the U.S. job market will be difficult to improve without a recession.
Currently, there is still a supply gap of more than 5 million in the U.S. labor market, and the labor participation rate is rising slowly, especially the labor participation rate of 25-54 year olds has approached its pre-epidemic high.
In addition, due to the excess savings and strong consumer credit of US residents, strong consumer demand will cause the impact of tightening policies on the job market to lag further.
The continued tight supply and demand in the U.S. job market will be the underlying tone of the U.S. economy in 2023.
In addition, as the interest rate hike is about to end and inflation expectations continue to fluctuate, we are not optimistic about the continued decline in wage growth.
Before the release of this data, the U.S. stock, bond and foreign exchange markets were overly optimistic about the Fed&#39;s path of interest rate hikes.
As inflation data continues to improve, the Federal Reserve has shortened the pace of interest rate hikes while maintaining a fragile balance in market inflation expectations. However, the market has turned a blind eye to the Fed&#39;s hawkish statements, and not only expects an early halt to rate hikes, but also expects two rate cuts by the end of the year.
With the supply and demand in the labor market tight and the impact of tightening policies unclear, we believe that the Fed&#39;s guidance on interest rate hikes at the end of the year is relatively reasonable. Adjustments to extreme market expectations and trading congestion may cause some damage to the market.
Despite this, the stubborn wage growth rate cannot change the current trend of rapid decline in inflation. With the M2 data turning negative year-on-year and the gradual improvement of various CPI sub-item leading indicators, the US CPI data has shifted to a rapid decline since October. The stubborn wage growth rate will only provide a bottom line for future inflation data. The current market expectations are difficult to falsify, and the market may enter a new round of game after the next inflation data is released.
