On November 13, 1989, four days after the Berlin Wall, which had separated East and West Berlin for 28 years, came down, Modrow had said he would help turn East Germany into a democracy.
At the time, communist leaders were forced to step down as protesters across East Germany demanded democracy and freedom.
After coming to power in the Soviet Union, Mikhail Gorbachev called for changes in Soviet-dominated Eastern Europe as well.
In March 1990, Modrow announced the first and only free elections in the German Democratic Republic (GDR).
The election results resulted in him no longer being prime minister.
Despite Modelo&#39;s reforms, opponents accused him of trying to delay political change and unification, which was to take place in October 1990.
