Modrow was born in 1928 in the then German town of Jasenitz (now Jasienica in Poland) and trained as a mechanic.
During World War II, he served as a platoon leader in a youth fire brigade, and near the end of the conflict became a member of the Nazi militia, the Volkssturm, which conscripted men aged 16 to 60 to fight in the final struggle of the war.
At 17, Modrow was captured by Soviet troops and taken as a prisoner of war to the Soviet Union, where he attended anti-fascist courses and became a committed Communist.
He returned in 1949, the year East Germany was founded, found work as a mechanic and went on to study social sciences and economics, earning a doctorate.
Modrow was a functionary of the Free German Youth Movement, to which nearly all young people in East Germany belonged, and rose through the ruling Socialist Unity Party (SED) from 1973 to 1989 to become chairman of the party in the Dresden region.
He also served in East Germany&#39;s parliament for more than 30 years.
In 1990 Modrow became the de facto leader of East Germany, holding the highest state post.
