Turkey-Syria earthquake relief efforts continue day and night
Since the strong earthquake struck Turkey and neighboring Syria, rescue teams from dozens of countries have been working day and night in the ruins of thousands of destroyed buildings to rescue survivors buried under the rubble.
In freezing temperatures, they frequently called for silence as they strained to hear any sounds of life from the crumbling pile of concrete.
Two more women have been rescued after surviving in the earthquake rubble for days, Reuters reported today.
However, the death toll from the earthquake climbed to 24,150.
The death toll in Türkiye is 20,665, and in Syria it is over 3,500.
Monday&#39;s 7.8-magnitude earthquake, which continued with several strong aftershocks in Turkey and Syria, is the seventh-deadliest natural disaster of the century, surpassing Japan&#39;s 2011 earthquake and tsunami and approaching the 31,000 deaths from a 2003 earthquake in neighboring Iran.
A similarly powerful earthquake in northwestern Türkiye in 1999 killed more than 17,000 people.
Rescuers pulled two women from the rubble of a collapsed building in Turkey after they were trapped for 122 hours following the region&#39;s deadliest earthquake in 20 years, authorities said on Saturday.
Another injured man was identified as Masallah Cicek, 55, who was rescued from the rubble of a collapsed building in Diyarbakir, the largest city in southeastern Turkey.
In freezing temperatures, rescuers frequently called for silence as they strained to hear any sounds of life emerging from the crumbling pile of concrete.
In Turkey&#39;s Samandag district, rescuers crouched under a slab of concrete, whispering &quot;Inshallah&quot; - &quot;God bless&quot; - as they carefully reached into the rubble and rescued a 10-day-old newborn.
His eyes widened as baby Yagiz Ulas was wrapped in a thermal blanket and carried to the field hospital.
Video images showed emergency workers also taking away his mother, who was dazed and pale but conscious on a stretcher.
Turkey&#39;s Vice President Fuat Oktay told reporters overnight that 67 people had been pulled from the rubble in the past 24 hours, with 31,000 rescue workers deployed in the affected areas.
He said about 80,000 people were being treated in hospitals, while 1.05 million people left homeless by the quake were crammed into makeshift shelters.
With many people lacking food in freezing winter conditions, questions are growing about the two countries&#39; leaders&#39; response to the disaster.
Syrian President Bashar al-Assad traveled to a hospital in Aleppo with his wife Asma, reportedly his first visit to the affected area since the earthquake, according to Syrian state media.
Earlier, the World Food Program said it was running out of stocks in rebel-held northwest Syria as the state of war complicated relief efforts.
On Friday, Erdogan visited Türkiye&#39;s Adıyaman province, where he acknowledged that the government&#39;s response had not been as fast as expected.
Opponents have seized on the issue to attack Erdogan, who is up for re-election in a May 14 vote that could be delayed because of the disaster.
Reuters said anger over delays in delivering aid and launching rescue efforts could affect the election.
Even before the earthquake, the vote was seen as the toughest challenge to Erdogan&#39;s two decades in power.
Erdogan called for unity and condemned what he called a &quot;negative campaign for political gain.&quot;
Türkiye&#39;s main opposition leader Kemal Kilicdaroglu criticized the government&#39;s response.
The criticism stated, “The earthquake was big, but what was worse than the earthquake was the lack of coordination, lack of planning and incompetence.
